section.p:
Let D be a closed and bounded domain in \mathbb{R}^n. Then, since it is bounded, it is contained in a cuboid \mathcal{C} = [a_1, b_1] \times \cdots \times [a_n , b_n]. Now suppose f: D \to \mathbb{R} is a continuous function on D. At the moment, it does not make sense to integrate f(x_1, \ldots, x_n) over the domain D, because we have only defined such integrals over cuboids and f is not defined for points not in D. To make sense of such a concept then, we extend our function f to all of \mathcal{C} by taking

            \tilde{f} (x_1, \ldots, x_n) = \begin{cases}
            f(x_1, \ldots, x_n) \amp \text{ if } (x_1, \ldots, x_n) \text{ is in } D, \\ 0 \amp \text{ otherwise.}
            \end{cases}

statement.p:
If D is a compact domain in \mathbb{R}^n with smooth boundary and f is continuous on D, then the multiple integral 

                \idotsint_\mathcal{D} f(x_1, \ldots, x_n) \, \tder{}{V}

                exists.
